The words for sick in the various verses are different Greek words and may be better translated "weak" and "weary" respectively. Mutual confession of sin and prayer will help us in our suffering from descending to this point of weakness and weariness." /></Paragraph><Paragraph /><Paragraph><UriLink Uri="https://faithlife.com/425268"><Run Text="Christian Wagner" /></UriLink><Run Text="
" /><Run Text="Apr 19, 2017 5:37 PM GMT" /></Paragraph><Paragraph /><Paragraph><Run Text="I appreciate the pastoral concern for encouraging the weary, but I believe the word 'sick' is correctly translated here, as seen in almost all available Bible translations. Do you really believe, that 99% of Bible translators get it wrong here? 

The word for sick in v.14 is 'asteneo' and used when Jesus was healing the sick about a dozen times, including when Lazarus was sick (" /><Reference IsLink="True" Reference="bible.64.11.1"><Run Text="Jn 11:1" /></Reference><Run Text="). Was Lazarus just 'weary'? 

Additionally translating 'kamnota' in v.15 as 'sick' makes sense in this context, because v.16 refers to being 'healed' (iaomai). Compare this to " /><Reference IsLink="True" Reference="bible.63.9.2"><Run Text="Luke 9:2" /></Reference><Run Text=" where Jesus "sent them... to heal (iaomai) the sick."
